english:
  title: A Record of the Community Fund of Milyang
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Park Mun-son, a former official of the Court of Propriety, came to visit me one day at my humble home and asked, "Why did the ancients place such importance on community bonds?"

    I replied, "Consider how fortune smiles upon us—to be born in the same age, midst the boundless expanse between heaven and earth, is no small blessing. Yet the five regions lie scattered far and wide, east and west, north and south stretch distant, and meetings between people are uncertain as wind and cloud. But when we share not only an age, but a nation, and share not only a nation, but a township—is there any fortune greater than this? Confucius spoke truly when he said, 'All within the four seas are brothers.' How much more so when we are born of the same land and dwell in the same village? Though we may not share blood or ancestry, how can our hearts not be moved toward kindness and duty?

    This is why the ancient kings planted trees in the village lanes, teaching people to aid one another in coming and going, to watch over one another in danger, to support each other in sickness. They wove affection through their bonds and grace through their words. Those who refused such teaching faced punishment for lacking propriety, harmony, responsibility, and compassion. The ancients understood human nature deeply.

    But as the world declined, propriety faded. The people's hearts grew shallow. Even kinfolk living in the same village now regard each other as strangers from distant lands. How much more so for those without family ties? In our Eastern lands, the customs of the Three Kingdoms fell short of the ancient ways of Kija. The ways of Koryŏ fell short of the Three Kingdoms. And can our present age dare claim to match Koryŏ's? One example reveals all three. Judge our town, and you shall know the rest."

    Park sighed deeply. "Alas, is it truly so? And yet the innate goodness heaven grants us endures eternal as a single day. Change depends on human will. Could we not restore the old ways here in our town?"

    I answered, "Your words touch upon this very matter—this is no mere local blessing but a great aid to the enlightened rule of our kingdom. Yet customs worn smooth by ages cannot return to their former purity in a single dawn. Still, there is hope."

    Park continued, "Though our town lies remote by the sea, far from the capital, our mountains are majestic and our fields fertile. The noble families and scholar-clans dwelling here are numerous. For all matters of joy and sorrow, great and small, we must gather together. On fortunate days, we must celebrate the peace we share. The officials sent here practice the old village regulations, and I have seen that worthy people do exist among us. If through such gatherings we might nurture a return to virtue, that is my deepest wish."

    I said, "Without a foundation in loyalty and sincerity, mere ceremony remains hollow. But if we root our efforts in these virtues and persevere without wavering, we may yet transform our people's hearts. Tell me—from where shall we draw these resources?"

    Park replied, "The ancients established community funds and community fields. Our prefect, the honored Park, when serving as magistrate, showed great kindness to the elders. Upon his return to court, he left bolts of cloth and measures of grain. The community leaders gathered together what had been given and established this fund. We collect and disburse with the seasons, keeping the principal intact and using only the surplus. Each year follows the same practice. This is our approach."

    I asked, "Good. But who ensures the stewards remain honest and expenditures stay measured? Without such care, depletion shall come swiftly."

    Park answered, "When harvests are lean or abundant, prices rise and fall. As tasks increase or decrease, so must our spending adjust. We must be responsive to circumstance. As for our stewards—even a village of ten families contains those of integrity. Our town is large; why should we fear lacking virtuous people? Those without compassion are beyond help. But any with a heart for righteousness will exert themselves to the utmost for the town's flourishing. I am confident this fund will endure."

    I said, "You speak wisdom. This is sufficient." And so I write this record.
  footnotes:
    - '子夏 (Zixia): A prominent disciple of Confucius, known for emphasizing the importance of community and filial piety.'
    - '枌楡 (fenyú): Specific trees planted in village lanes by ancient Chinese rulers as symbols of community gathering.'
    - '不婣不睦不任不恤 (Four failures): Lack of propriety, disharmony, irresponsibility, and lack of compassion—traditional Confucian categories of social failure.'
    - '義田 and 義財: Ancient Chinese institutions of communal land and communal funds established for the welfare of villages.'
    - '箕邦: A reference to the legendary ancient kingdom established by Kija (箕子), representing the ideal age of virtue.'
    - '十室之邑：必有忠信 (A village of ten families must contain loyal people): A paraphrasing of Confucian wisdom on the universality of virtue among humans.'
